30/10/2007
Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) Presidency Chairman Zeljko Komsic wrapped up a three-day visit to Rome on Thursday (October 25th) where he met with a number of religious, political and business officials. On Wednesday, Komsic met with Italian President Giorgio Napolitano to discuss the political situation in BiH. On Thursday, Komsic was received by Pope Benedict XVI. 
*** 
Hungary appreciates Macedonia's progress in the past years and views the country as a factor for stability in the Balkans, Hungarian Foreign Minister Kinga Goncz said on Monday (October 29th), after meeting her visiting Macedonian counterpart, Antonio Milososki. The deputy speaker of the Hungarian Parliament, Laszlo Mandur, also met with Milososki, reiterating Hungary's support for EU and NATO enlargement. 
*** 
 Albanian President Bamir Topi paid his first official visit to Macedonia, meeting with counterpart Branko Crvenkovski. They agreed that Macedonia and Albania have common goals -- EU and NATO membership, maintaining good political relations and building on their potential for economic-co-operation. Topi also reiterated support for former UN envoy Martti Ahtisaari's status plan for Kosovo, saying he would visit other states in the region to lobby for it. 
*** 
Albanian Prime Minister Sali Berisha met with Egyptian Foreign Minister Ahmed Aboul Gheit on Monday (October 29th) during an official visit to Egypt. Berisha urged Cairo to support Kosovo's independence and to ask the countries of the Islamic Conference to recognise Kosovo's independence as a group. 
*** 
Romanian Prime Minister Calin Popescu Tariceanu and his visiting Turkish counterpart Recep Tayyip Erdogan vowed on Thursday (October 25th) in Bucharest that the two countries will decisively contribute to the promotion of economic and development projects in the region. They agreed to encourage mutual investments and to step up energy and transport infrastructure co-operation with the Caucasus, Central Asia and the Middle East. 
*** 
Bosnia and Herzegovina presidency member Haris Silajdzic met with Montenegrin President Filip Vujanovic in Budva, Montenegro, on Thursday (October 25th). They discussed bilateral relations and Euro-Atlantic integration prospects. 
*** 
Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica met with Slovenian Foreign Minister Dimitrij Rupel on Wednesday (October 24th) in Belgrade. They discussed the Kosovo status process. Rupel said Slovenia, which takes up the rotating EU presidency on January 1st, would not take up any unilateral moves regarding Kosovo and would co-ordinate its position with other EU members. Rupel also met with President Boris Tadic and Foreign Minister Vuk Jeremic. 
(Various sources 23/10/07-30/10/07)
